{#- OPERATOR — who recovers it past the surface + fit stats -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-help-data-recovery-operator" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">Who recovers it</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">A Certified ProAdvisor recovers the data and rebuilds the books.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Clicking restore is the easy part. The work that actually gets you a usable file is everything around it: figuring out which copy &mdash; ADR, backup, or transaction log &mdash; holds the most recent good data, combining a recent <code>.TLG</code> with the last good <code>.QBW</code> to recover transactions since the backup, verifying the recovered file is sound before you trust it, and rebuilding the books to a CPA-ready standard so the numbers tie again. A Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor with active Online and Desktop certifications does that against a written scope. We recover and rebuild the <em>books</em> from the files that are available; hardware-level drive recovery and ransomware remediation are specialist and IT work we coordinate with, not perform. Independent firm &mdash; an Intuit account, login, or billing matter stays with Intuit.</p>
    </div>
